25/08/2006

The Finnish mobile phone equipment manufacturer Nokia announced that it would expand its current WCDMA 3G radio network contract with the Greek telecom provider TIM Hellas and provide more services. 
Nokia is TIM Hellas's sole 3G network supplier. 
The new services will include Nokia Flexi WCDMA base station, Mobile TV and Nokia Spare Parts Management. 
No financial details were released.
***
Macedonia's energy regulators approved the power utility ESM Distribucija's request to boost electricity prices, effective on 1 September. 
The regulatory commission decided that the prices would be raised by 9.14 per cent, although ESM Distribucja had asked for twice that amount. 
After the adjustment, end-prices for household consumers will be raised to 0.04822 euros per kWh, while industrial clients will pay 0.02964 per kWh.
***
Fitch Ratings upgraded the credit ratings of Zagrebacka Banka -- Croatia's  third largest-- by two notches to BBB+. 
The short-term rating was brought up from F3 to F2, while the individual rating at C/D and support rating at 2 were affirmed. 
According to Fitch Ratings, the move was in line with the upgrade of Croatia's country ceiling to BBB+.
***
Hungary's OTP Bank has submitted a binding bid for the purchase of an 80 per cent or greater share in Montenegro's Crnogorska Komercijalna Banka (CKB). 
No details were disclosed about the financial parameters of the offer. 
CKB has a market share of around 43 per cent and is owned by minority shareholders, including Telekom Montenegro (11.5 per cent) and foreign entities.
***
Republika Srpska's industrial growth fell by 2.4 per cent year-on-year in July 2006, following 10.2 per cent year-on-year growth in June, according to official data. 
The decline was attributed to weak performance in manufacturing, which registered a 6.1 per cent year-on-year output drop in July. 
Production growth of food and beverages decelerated from 32.8 per cent year-on-year in June to 7.8 per cent year-on-year in July.
***
Croatia's registered jobless rate dropped to 15.7 per cent year-on-year in July, down by 1.2 percentage points year-on-year and 0.3 percentage points month-on-month, according to preliminary data from the statistical bureau. 
The number of unemployed declined by 7.6 per cent year-on-year in July.
***
Foreign direct investment (FDI) in Romania increased by 52 per cent year-on-year in the first half of 2006, reaching 3.1 billion euros, according to the latest data from the central bank. 
FDI covered 77.8 per cent of the current account deficit reported during the period.
(Various sources 18/08/06 - 25/08/06)
